CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) commands are used to style and layout web pages. Here are some common CSS commands:

Selector: Selects the HTML element that you want to apply a style to. For example, h1 selects all <h1> elements.

Property: Specifies the style to apply to the selected element. For example, color sets the color of the text.

Value: Specifies the value for the selected property. For example, color: blue; sets the color of the text to blue.

Here are some common CSS commands:

color: Sets the color of the text.
background-color: Sets the background color of an element.
font-size: Sets the size of the font.
font-family: Sets the font family to use.
text-align: Sets the alignment of the text.
border: Sets the border of an element.
padding: Sets the padding of an element.
margin: Sets the margin of an element.
display: Sets how an element is displayed.
position: Sets the position of an element.
float: Sets the horizontal alignment of an element.
clear: Clears the float on an element.
opacity: Sets the opacity of an element.
z-index: Sets the stacking order of an element.
transition: Sets the transition effect on an element.
